  { q: "What's the difference between Forno Bravo Modena, Napolino, and Professionale?", a: "Three distinct Forno Bravo commercial wood-fired pizza oven lines. <b>Modena</b> is the commercial mid-volume line — Modena 120 (smaller), Modena 140 (mid-size), Modena 160 (larger) sized across different pizza-production throughput requirements. Common at LA Italian-heritage restaurants and mid-volume Neapolitan operations. <b>Napolino</b> is smaller-format commercial — designed for space-constrained commercial kitchens needing Italian-style wood-fired cooking without full Modena footprint. <b>Professionale</b> is the flagship artisan line — higher spec, heavier construction, premium appointments for upscale restaurant installations. Plus Vesuvio is the high-capacity commercial variant; Roma is the modular configuration for complex installation footprints. Each model uses traditional Italian brick-oven construction with California-manufactured execution." },
  { q: "Do you service Forno Bravo at LA Italian restaurants?", a: "Yes — Forno Bravo installations cluster at LA Italian-heritage restaurants and Neapolitan pizza operations. Specific operations: Felix Trattoria (Venice), Valentino (Santa Monica), Piccolo Paradiso (Beverly Hills), Bottega Louie (DTLA), various smaller Italian-concept restaurants across the city. The Forno Bravo positioning serves Italian-heritage operations that want authentic Italian brick-oven cooking technology but prefer California-manufactured execution over direct Italian imports (Moretti Forni Milan, Valoriani Florence, Pavesi). California manufacturing plus Italian-heritage design is the distinctive combination. Service requires wood-fired oven specialization — same diagnostic domains as Wood Stone service (flame-impingement, refractory, LADBS chimney compliance), though Forno Bravo construction differs from Wood Stone execution." },
  { q: "What's distinct about Forno Bravo service vs Wood Stone service?", a: "Both brands are wood-fired pizza oven specialists but differ in construction and service approach. <b>Wood Stone</b> uses castable ceramic refractory construction typical of Pacific Northwest manufacturing tradition; hybrid Mt Adams models integrate gas-boost prominently. <b>Forno Bravo</b> uses traditional Italian brick-oven construction — refractory brick assembled in specific patterns (barrel vault, Pompeii style, Toscana style) that influence heat radiation characteristics and cooking patterns. Service on Forno Bravo includes brick inspection and pointing (mortar maintenance between bricks), traditional Italian-design draft calibration, and wood-fired-only or hybrid (fewer hybrid models than Wood Stone) cooking-mode service. Both brands require California gas compliance for hybrid models (CARB Title 20, LADBS chimney requirements)." },
  { q: "What does Forno Bravo pizza oven repair cost in LA?", a: "$120 flat commercial diagnostic, waived with repair. Typical Forno Bravo service ranges: thermostat (where installed) $200–$340, door gasket / seal $220–$380, oven-door thermocouple (where installed) $220–$380, brick pointing and mortar maintenance $360–$620, flame-impingement calibration $320–$560, refractory brick replacement (section) $450–$800, refractory brick replacement (major section or oven-floor) $800–$1,500, chimney inspection + LADBS compliance verification $300–$500, gas valve (hybrid models, rare) $280–$480, burner ignitor (hybrid models) $240–$400. Most Forno Bravo calls land $380–$750 parts-and-labor. Traditional brick-oven refurbish work runs at the higher end due to specialized masonry service. See our <a href=\"/price-list/commercial-oven-repair-cost/\">commercial oven repair cost guide</a>." }
];

